{"key":"processedPost-8574079","value":{"id":8574079,"first":8573958,"last":8575016,"when":1214674642,"utime":"06/28/08 08:37 PM","content":"Another alternative is to place the tray in the sink and allow the faucet to slowly fill it up and run over the edges.&nbsp; Let the water run gently for three or four hours and then drain off whatever will drain out, and place back into fruiting conditions.&nbsp; Put a glass full of water or similar on top of the substrate to hold it submerged.<br />Cased cakes tend to shoot their wad on the first flush, so if you got a really good one, don't expect much from the second.&nbsp; If you got a puny first flush, it might do better the second time.&nbsp; Personally, I've found cakes produce more total product when fruited as cakes over several flushes, dunking between each flush.<br />RR","title":"Re: rehydration"}}